description:
Bug 38131ajc needs to have the '-d .' option specified. I am using 1.1rc1. This behavior is a regression since rc1 and differs from javac. I suspect it may be related to a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce this issue, create a class in a subpackage as shown below:

```java
package subpackage;

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}
```

Then compile the class using the following command:

```
ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java
```

You will notice that a directory named "subpackage" is created within the existing "subpackage" directory instead of the root directory. This behavior is not observed when using javac.

This issue does not have a major impact, but it should still be addressed.
